覧ﾙFarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/scripts.mdﾙ@0c9ff2bf4975ad0cf136732bb467ab74e6a0bdf98d260df958361c335ca6ae9fｧScripts息ScriptsﾚeIn Nushell, you can write and run scripts in the Nushell language. To run a script, you can pass it as an argument to the 
``nu``
 commandline application:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
nu myscript.nu

```
This will run the script to completion in a new instance of Nu. You can also run scripts inside the 
current
 instance of Nu using 
[link: /commands/docs/source.md] ``source``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
source myscript.nu

```
Let's look at an example script file:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# myscript.nu
def greet [name] {
  ["hello" $name]
}

greet "world"

```
A script file defines the definitions for custom commands as well as the main script itself, which will run after the custom commands are defined.
In the above example, first 
``greet``
 is defined by the Nushell interpreter. This allows us to later call this definition. We could have written the above as:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
greet "world"

def greet [name] {
  ["hello" $name]
}

```
There is no requirement that definitions have to come before the parts of the script that call the definitions, allowing you to put them where you feel comfortable.
註接亀itle: Scripts
Path: Scripts
Content:
In Nushell, you can write and run scripts in the Nushell language. To run a script, you can pass it as an argument to the 
``nu``
 commandline application:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
nu myscript.nu

```
This will run the script to completion in a new instance of Nu. You can also run scripts inside the 
current
 instance of Nu using 
[link: /commands/docs/source.md] ``source``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
source myscript.nu

```
Let's look at an example script file:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# myscript.nu
def greet [name] {
  ["hello" $name]
}

greet "world"

```
A script file defines the definitions for custom commands as well as the main script itself, which will run after the custom commands are defined.
In the above example, first 
``greet``
 is defined by the Nushell interpreter. This allows us to later call this definition. We could have written the above as:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
greet "world"

def greet [name] {
  ["hello" $name]
}

```
There is no requirement that definitions have to come before the parts of the script that call the definitions, allowing you to put them where you feel comfortable.
麟Farchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/scripts.mdﾙ@dc0306bec2da242bc74a93607ed7c6c77b380bb4ca74a5849cf47dcd812473a4ｧScripts損How Scripts are ProcessedﾙﾞIn a script, definitions run first. This allows us to call the definitions using the calls in the script.
After the definitions run, we start at the top of the script file and run each group of commands one after another.
註接Title: Scripts
Path: How Scripts are Processed
Content:
In a script, definitions run first. This allows us to call the definitions using the calls in the script.
After the definitions run, we start at the top of the script file and run each group of commands one after another.
麟Farchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/scripts.mdﾙ@0a8bdf7156a86a08c1c3a15f288f5a8d0b2e4ceba611d6d269eaf055d2b6ac45ｧScripts速Script LinesﾚjTo better understand how Nushell sees lines of code, let's take a look at an example script:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
a
b; c | d

```
When this script is run, Nushell will first run the 
``a``
 command to completion and view its results. Next, Nushell will run 
``b; c | d``
 following the rules in the 
[link: pipelines.html#semicolons] "Semicolons" section
.
註接謬itle: Scripts
Path: Script Lines
Content:
To better understand how Nushell sees lines of code, let's take a look at an example script:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
a
b; c | d

```
When this script is run, Nushell will first run the 
``a``
 command to completion and view its results. Next, Nushell will run 
``b; c | d``
 following the rules in the 
[link: pipelines.html#semicolons] "Semicolons" section
.
麟Farchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/scripts.mdﾙ@7a6b35b7d81141235dc53178d55048ead0e82946a66ce7ec2459cd04b2617715ｧScripts存Parameterizing ScriptsﾚｮScript files can optionally contain a special "main" command. 
``main``
 will be run after any other Nu code, and is primarily used to allow positional parameters and flags in scripts. You can pass arguments to scripts after the script name (
``nu <script name> <script args>``
).
For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# myscript.nu
def main [x: int] {
  $x + 10
}

```
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
nu myscript.nu 100
# => 110

```
註接綉itle: Scripts
Path: Parameterizing Scripts
Content:
Script files can optionally contain a special "main" command. 
``main``
 will be run after any other Nu code, and is primarily used to allow positional parameters and flags in scripts. You can pass arguments to scripts after the script name (
``nu <script name> <script args>``
).
For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# myscript.nu
def main [x: int] {
  $x + 10
}

```
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
nu myscript.nu 100
# => 110

```
麟Farchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/scripts.mdﾙ@2347296b66714fa5f0c473be55f6e99b6882437a1defaf32ea72764ad2d74db7ｧScripts他Argument Type Interpretationﾚ
By default, arguments provided to a script are interpreted with the type 
``Type::Any``
, implying that they are not constrained to a specific data type and can be dynamically interpreted as fitting any of the available data types during script execution.
In the previous example, 
``main [x: int]``
 denotes that the argument x should possess an integer data type. However, if arguments are not explicitly typed, they will be parsed according to their apparent data type.
For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# implicit_type.nu
def main [x] {
  $"Hello ($x | describe) ($x)"
}

# explicit_type.nu
def main [x: string] {
  $"Hello ($x | describe) ($x)"
}

```
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
nu implicit_type.nu +1
# => Hello int 1

nu explicit_type.nu +1
# => Hello string +1

```
註接ETitle: Scripts
Path: Argument Type Interpretation
Content:
By default, arguments provided to a script are interpreted with the type 
``Type::Any``
, implying that they are not constrained to a specific data type and can be dynamically interpreted as fitting any of the available data types during script execution.
In the previous example, 
``main [x: int]``
 denotes that the argument x should possess an integer data type. However, if arguments are not explicitly typed, they will be parsed according to their apparent data type.
For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# implicit_type.nu
def main [x] {
  $"Hello ($x | describe) ($x)"
}

# explicit_type.nu
def main [x: string] {
  $"Hello ($x | describe) ($x)"
}

```
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
nu implicit_type.nu +1
# => Hello int 1

nu explicit_type.nu +1
# => Hello string +1

```
麟Farchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/scripts.mdﾙ@e04f74e5f40ceec5e123ba1d034e88cad0d8bce7b998c1098a276a11fc0bbd7dｧScripts足SubcommandsﾚxA script can have multiple 
[link: custom_commands.html#subcommands] subcommands
, like 
``run``
 or 
``build``
 for example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# myscript.nu
def "main run" [] {
    print "running"
}

def "main build" [] {
    print "building"
}

def main [] {
    print "hello from myscript!"
}

```
You can then execute the script's subcommands when calling it:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
nu myscript.nu
# => hello from myscript!
nu myscript.nu build
# => building
nu myscript.nu run
# => running

```
[link: modules.html#main] Unlike modules
, 
``main``
 does 
not
 need to be exported in order to be visible. In the above example, our 
``main``
 command is not 
``export def``
, however it was still executed when running 
``nu myscript.nu``
. If we had used myscript as a module by running 
``use myscript.nu``
, rather than running 
``myscript.nu``
 as a script, trying to execute the 
``myscript``
 command would not work since 
``myscript``
 is not exported.
It is important to note that you must define a 
``main``
 command in order for subcommands of 
``main``
 to be correctly exposed. For example, if we had just defined the 
``run``
 and 
``build``
 subcommands, they wouldn't be accessible when running the script:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# myscript.nu
def "main run" [] {
    print "running"
}

def "main build" [] {
    print "building"
}

```
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
nu myscript.nu build
nu myscript.nu run

```
This is a limitation of the way scripts are currently processed. If your script only has subcommands, you can add an empty 
``main``
 to expose the subcommands, like so:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
def main [] {}

```
註接｢Title: Scripts
Path: Subcommands
Content:
A script can have multiple 
[link: custom_commands.html#subcommands] subcommands
, like 
``run``
 or 
``build``
 for example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# myscript.nu
def "main run" [] {
    print "running"
}

def "main build" [] {
    print "building"
}

def main [] {
    print "hello from myscript!"
}

```
You can then execute the script's subcommands when calling it:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
nu myscript.nu
# => hello from myscript!
nu myscript.nu build
# => building
nu myscript.nu run
# => running

```
[link: modules.html#main] Unlike modules
, 
``main``
 does 
not
 need to be exported in order to be visible. In the above example, our 
``main``
 command is not 
``export def``
, however it was still executed when running 
``nu myscript.nu``
. If we had used myscript as a module by running 
``use myscript.nu``
, rather than running 
``myscript.nu``
 as a script, trying to execute the 
``myscript``
 command would not work since 
``myscript``
 is not exported.
It is important to note that you must define a 
``main``
 command in order for subcommands of 
``main``
 to be correctly exposed. For example, if we had just defined the 
``run``
 and 
``build``
 subcommands, they wouldn't be accessible when running the script:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# myscript.nu
def "main run" [] {
    print "running"
}

def "main build" [] {
    print "building"
}

```
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
nu myscript.nu build
nu myscript.nu run

```
This is a limitation of the way scripts are currently processed. If your script only has subcommands, you can add an empty 
``main``
 to expose the subcommands, like so:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
def main [] {}

```
麟Farchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/book/scripts.mdﾙ@1f53c4713aa3962a2508dda58f7e493ad2f417a3a9333891ed41d8efd17ce6aaｧScripts贈)ﾚチ`#!``
On Linux and macOS you can optionally use a 
[link: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shebang_(Unix)] shebang
 to tell the OS that a file should be interpreted by Nu. For example, with the following in a file named 
``myscript``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
#!/usr/bin/env nu
"Hello World!"

```
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
./myscript
# => Hello World!

```
For script to have access to standard input, 
``nu``
 should be invoked with 
``--stdin``
 flag:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
#!/usr/bin/env -S nu --stdin
def main [] {
  echo $"stdin: ($in)"
}

```
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
echo "Hello World!" | ./myscript
# => stdin: Hello World!

```
註接｣Title: Scripts
Path: )
Content:
``#!``
On Linux and macOS you can optionally use a 
[link: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shebang_(Unix)] shebang
 to tell the OS that a file should be interpreted by Nu. For example, with the following in a file named 
``myscript``
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
#!/usr/bin/env nu
"Hello World!"

```
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
./myscript
# => Hello World!

```
For script to have access to standard input, 
``nu``
 should be invoked with 
``--stdin``
 flag:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
#!/usr/bin/env -S nu --stdin
def main [] {
  echo $"stdin: ($in)"
}

```
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
echo "Hello World!" | ./myscript
# => stdin: Hello World!

```
